This is a bug in the Tracker module you have installed as an add-on (contributed) plugin. The Tracker module declares two strings: 
```text
$string['errorinvalidelementid'] = 'Invalid element. Cannot edit element id';
$string['errorinvalidelementID'] = 'Element ID is not set';
```
 As you can see, the identifiers of these two strings are the same but the letter case. That leads to the conflict and error when the language customization tool is trying to check-out strings. You may wish to report this as a bug in the Tracker module. If uninstalling the Tracker module is not an option for you, you will need to fix its code and make sure that these two string ids are really different.

You may, or may not know, that it is possible for languages to include a styles.php file, and then if the current theme specifies both $THEME->standardsheets = true and $THEME->langsheets = true (both of those are the default), then the styles.php file from the language folder will be included with the rest of the standard theme CSS . Well, that was the situation in Moodle 1.9. However, looking in CVS , only Vietnamese includes a styles.php file (last modified in 2005), and that only says 
```text
body,td,tr,li {
 font-family: Arial, Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif !important;
}
```
 Which looks very similar to the CSS in the standard theme: 
```text
body, table, td, th, li {
 font-family:Arial, Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif;
}
```
 I can't work out why this was introduced. ( http://cvs.moodle.org/moodle/theme/standard/config.php?r1=1.13&r2=1.14 does not help much.) The one thing that might need it is right-to-left languages. However, these days we have a better way to handle that, using an optional rtl.css file in the theme folder. So, I am proposing to remove this functionality from Moodle 2.0. If anyone objects to that, please explain why ASAP. Thanks.

